Source: Panafrican News Agency, Sat 21 Oct 2000 [edited

Ebola Hemorrhagic Fever outbreak in Uganda Shows no sign of Let Up
------------------------------------------------------------------
KAMPALA: Ebola hemorrhagic fever cases in Uganda's northern district of Gulu
will continue to increase for the next 2 to 3 days before the
situation stabilizes, a senior health official said Saturday. Director Of
Health Services, Sam Zaramba, said volunteers and health workers have
identified about 200 people who had close contacts with Ebola patients and
these were being monitored. Over the last 48 hours up to Saturday, 28 new
cases were reported with 10 deaths in Lacor and Gulu district hospitals,
bringing the cumulative number of infections to 139 and 51 deaths since the
outbreak of the deadly disease in Uganda. [As of Sun 22 Oct 2000, the number
of cases had risen to 149 with 54 deaths. - Mod.CP. Zaramba attributed the
increase to the active case search of patients in the villages.
Out of the 88 patients still alive in the 2 hospitals, Zaramba said about
40 are already cured and waiting to be discharged, but simply kept for
observation. He said 48 patients are in different stages of recovery.
According to Zaramba, reports from all other districts in Uganda indicate
that there are no cases of Ebola other than in Gulu district. "The reported
suspected cases from Kakira hospital, some 80 km east of Kampala, and
Kajansi, near the capital city, are being investigated," he explained.
The virus has been identified as a strain last seen in southern Sudan in
1979. "This type is called Ebola Sudan. But this does not necessarily mean
it came from the Sudan. It has the same characteristics as it occurred in
the Sudan in 1979," Zaramba said.
Many people were already blaming the outbreak on returning Ugandan troops
from the DR Congo, which was hit by Ebola in 1995, but scientists say that
was a different strain. Another speculation is that the virus could have
been brought to Gulu by rebels of Uganda's Lord's Resistance Army, allegedly
operating from southern Sudan. The rebels have regularly raided areas in
Gulu, in their 13-year-old war against the Ugandan government.
According to World Health Organisation statistics, the disease has killed
793 0f its 1100 known cases, representing about 72 percent of the victims.
Scientists say the fatality rate of the disease in Uganda stands at 38.5
percent compared to between 50 and 90 percent fatality rate in the Sudan and
Congo.
