Date: Sun, 22 Oct 2000 09:31 (MDST)
From: Charles H. Calisher <calisher@promedmail.org>

Ebola Hemorrhagic Fever - Uganda: A Comment
-------------------------------------------
Allow me to point out that the designation of the virus presently causing
Ebola fever in Uganda, "Ebola-Sudan", does not at all indicate that the
source of the virus is Sudan. In spite of the index case having been traced
to the Sudan border, and the molecular characterization of the virus
indicating that it is close to prototype Ebola-Sudan virus, these are not
guarantees that the virus was imported from the Sudan. We simply do not know
enough about the distribution of Ebola-Sudan -- or the other Ebola strains
--in Africa.
One would not assume the source of Japanese encephalitis virus always is
Japan, or that a West Nile virus is from the Nile Valley, or that yellow
fever virus must turn someone yellow -- these simply are names.
Identification of the etiologic agent of Ebola fever in Uganda was done by
molecular genetic assays but the epidemiology, especially the origin of this
particular strain, remains to be determined. Part of the problem is the
nomenclature of the ebolaviruses. By naming them Ebola-Zaire, Ebola-Sudan,
Ebola-Cote d'Ivoire, etc. confusion was produced with regard to whether
these are distinct viruses (types) or subtypes of a single type (virus).
Either these things are the same virus, being variations on a single theme
(need one name plus a suffix), or they are distinct (need different names).
Bad enough that we have viruses that are numbered (bluetongue 1, bluetongue
2, etc., dengue 1, dengue 2, etc.), having many viruses all called "Ebola
virus" likewise is not clarifying.
In spite of the clear molecular basis for distinguishing between
ebolaviruses, classical serologic studies have not been done, so we really
do not know much about cross-protection or even antigenicity in general; at
least I do not. As Ogden Nash said, "Progress is a great thing but I think
it has gone on too long."
--
Charles H. Calisher, Ph.D.
AIDL, Department of Microbiology
Colorado State University
Fort Collins, CO 80523
<calisher@promedmail.org>
[As Dr. Calisher rightly points out the nomenclature of the filoviruses is
in a state of flux. The nomenclature adopted in the 7th Report of the
International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses, which is likely to be
provisional pending further elucidation of the relationships of the
different viruses, is that the currently named filoviruses be ranked as
virus species with the following designations (and their abbreviations):
Marburg virus (MARV), Cote d'Ivoire Ebola virus (CIEBOV), Reston Ebola virus
(REBOV), Sudan Ebola virus (SEBOV), and Zaire Ebola virus (ZEBOV). - Mod.CP
